################################################################################
#####
##### Ubuntu 22.04.5 Desktop on Laptop HP Pentium Gold:
#####
##### M.C. Felipe Raymundo Garcia Cavazos., 2 February 2026
#####
################################################################################

We are going to install Ubuntu 22.04.5 on a laptop with these steps:

- a new SSD with no OS installed on this and any other media.

- running a live Ubuntu 22.04.1 session from an USB.

- the Ubuntu 22.04.5 was downloaded to the lap SSD, from this an bootable USB
  was made, then the live session terminated and finally Ubuntu 22.04.5 was 
  installed from the new created USB.
  
- The lap SSD was partitiones and installed and Ubuntu 22.04.5 was installed on 
  on of those partitions, the other partition was left unformatted. 
  
  You can see the laptop specs on hp_pentium_gold_specs.txt which is a specs
  that is generated by running hp_pentium_gold_specs.sh on a bash terminal.

################################################################################

##### 0.- On BIOS:

          - to enter BIOS menu, press one time the power button and then 
            repeteadely ESC, F2 or F10
          - disable secure boot.
          - enable virtualization.
          - adjust date and time.
          - run cpu, hard disk and memory tests to verify that they are OK.
          - if you are using a latinamerican keyboard run this command to force
            Ubuntu to recognize a latiamerican keyboard.
            
            setxkbmap latam
          
##### 1.- After this, begin the live Ubuntu-22.04.1 session by:

       - turn off the lap from the BIOS session.
       - plug-in the USB with Ubuntu-22.04.1
       - press repeteadely ESC, F2 or F10 to open the menu with the USB boot 
         options and select: try Ubuntu.
       - after the live session begins, connect to the wifi.
          
##### 2.- Download the .iso:

wget -c https://releases.ubuntu.com/22.04.5/ubuntu-22.04.5-desktop-amd64.iso

##### 3.- Run lsblk to verify that thes system sees the SSD or the HDD. In this
          case lsblk said that nvme0n1 is the 0 disk with 238.5 G available.

##### 4. Format the SSD to ext4.

sudo mkfs.ext4 -v /dev/nvme0n1

##### 5.- Create the mounting folder:

sudo mkdir -pv /mnt/ssd

##### 6.- Mount the drive SSD.

sudo mount -v /dev/nvme0n1 /mnt/ssd

##### 7.- Give it full permissions.

sudo chmod -v 777 /mnt/ssd

##### 8.- Go to the mounting folder and begin the download.

cd /mnt/ssd

wget -c https://releases.ubuntu.com/22.04.5/ubuntu-22.04.5-desktop-amd64.iso

##### 9.- Download the official checksum file to your SSD

sync (Force the system to write all data to the SSD metal)

wget https://releases.ubuntu.com/22.04/SHA256SUMS

##### 10.- Tell the system to check the ISO against that official file
          (this command will say OK or FAILED).

sha256sum -c SHA256SUMS --ignore-missing

##### 11.- Plug the usb and identify it.

lsblk -o NAME,SIZE,TYPE,TRAN,MODEL

       In this case sdb1   14.8G part, is the plugged usb.

##### 12.- Create the bootable USB.

sudo dd if=ubuntu-22.04.5-desktop-amd64.iso of=/dev/sdb bs=4M status=progress \
        conv=fsync
        
##### 13.- Umount and unplug the the bootable USB to make room to plug 
           another USB or an external HDD to save the downloaded .iso
           
sudo unmount /dev/sdb1, then unplug it thge bootable USB.
        
##### 14.- Plug an external HDD or other USB to save the downloaded media.
           identify and mount it and create a folder to store the .iso. 
lsblk -f

sudo mkdir -pv /mnt/external_hdd

sudo mount -v /dev/sdc1 /mnt/external_hdd

##### 15.- Save the downloaded .iso to the external HDD.
         
sudo cp -v /mnt/ssd/ubuntu-22.04.5-desktop-amd64.iso /mnt/external_hdd/

##### 16.- Unmount the external HDD (were the .iso was stored) and the USB were
           the install media was created.Ã±

##### 17.- Unmount the SSD (that we used to save temporaly the .iso)
           Do not unplug yet the USB where the live session resides.
           
##### 18.- Terminate the live Ubuntu 22.04.1 session.

      - press the power button.
      - when the HP-Ubuntu screen appears, unplug the USB with Ubuntu 22.04.1
      
##### 19.- Now to begin Ubuntu-22.04.5 install

       - plug-in the USB with Ubuntu-22.04.1
       - press the power button one time and inmediately
       - press repeteadely ESS, F2 or F10 to open the USB menu boot option,
       - select: install Ubuntu to begin the installation process by Ubuntu GUI.

##### 20.- I choose the following options and partitions: 
  
       - choose minimal installation if you want.

       - Download updates while installing and install third party software and 
         wifi hardware, etc. 

       - I did't use the 'advanced features' on the first menu. 

       - Partition 1: The Boot Entry (EFI)

         Size: 512 MB (with the + button)

         Type for the new partition: Primary

         Location for the new partition: Beginning of this spac

         Click OK.

       - Partition 2: The Workstation (Ubuntu 135 GB)

         Size: 135000 MB (with the + button)

         Type for the new partition: Primary

         Location for the new partition: Beginning of this space

         Use as: Ext4 journaling file system

         Mount point: Select the / (the single forward slash).

         Click OK.
   
###### 21.- Click 'Install' to start the install process.

###### 22.- Select your location and time zone.

###### 23.- Select the log type: log in automatically, require my password to 
          log in and use active directory. (I selected to log in automatically)
          
###### 24.- Restart the machine.


       
       
      


